<p>
I <a href="/2014/04/Goodbye_Google_Hello_World">quit Google</a> back
at the end of April, after having been with them for almost four
years. During that time I got to work with some amazing folks in
YouTube and Search Ads. I never had any particularly interesting
grievances, and I'm not ruling out returning sooner or later. My
reasons for deciding to quit also seem to resonate with many &mdash;
living nearer my family in Sweden / Aruna's in Kazakhstan,
pursuing more freedom in time &amp; in space (where I can live and
travel, and how I allocate my time).</p>

<p>When talking to various folks since then, there almost invariably
comes a point in the conversation where they go &ldquo;so&hellip; what are
you going to do now?&rdquo;. This post attempts to describe some of my
thinking on this topic, introducing a phrase that I've been using
in one-on-one conversation with people; I am going to be
<em>Actively Irresponsible</em>.</p>

<p>By this I mean two things:</p>
<ul>
<li><em>Irresponsible:</em> I will aim to take on a minimum of
external responsibilities in the next several months, to allow me to
pursue ideas and projects I've been thinking and talking about for a
long time, but haven't been feasible for me to work on during
full-time employment at a major company.</li>
<li><em>Active:</em> I'm not planning to just rest on my
laurels. While I may be technically <em>arbetsl&ouml;s</em>
(<em>un</em>employed in Swedish, with the same literal meaning
as in English &mdash; without work), I much prefer the Norwegian
phrase for the same concept, which is
<em>arbeidsfri</em> &mdash; work<em>free</em>.
</li>
</ul>

<p>It goes without saying that I am enormously privileged to be in a
position where I don't need to immediately jump back into regular
employment on the terms of whoever will employ me, due to having some
savings and low expenses. I'm enormously appreciative of this
opportunity.</p>

<p>Of course the needle will swing back towards pragmatism and I'll
focus on making money as a primary goal and not just a nice
side-effectof other projects at some point, if savings run low and
depending on how things shake out. I hope to be able to do this on my
terms, though, without backing down from the other aims listed
below too much.</p>

<h1><a href="#doing_what" id="doing_what">Active doing what, then?</a></h1>
<p>Here I've described some of the things I am doing and planning to
be doing with my time in the near- to medium-term. Notably absent here
