<h2><a href="#efficiency" id="efficiency">Improving the efficiency of my tools</a></h2>
<p>Like most technical workers, I have a setup in terms of editors,
tools, ways of working, etc. that's &ldquo;good enough&rdquo; to let
me get the job done, but I constantly feel that good engineering
principles &amp; my own design esthetics are in tension with
short-term delivery dates and the need to feel productive at
work. Without as much time pressures, I have no good excuse for ugly
hacks, but can step back and think through what it is I'm trying to
achieve, at least within areas that matter to me.</p>

<p>There still needs to be a reflective component in the process to
avoid putting oceans of time towards polishing insignificant details,
but I believe it could be a productive activity for me to try to
tackle problems that keep bugging me &mdash; if I hit upon something
that truly improves my own efficiency, I may not be the only one that
would benefit.</p>

<p>Some things I believe are important within this topic:</p>
<ul>
<li><em>Be data-driven:</em> The way to tell whether you are doing
things effectively is to quantify some metrics that track what you
care about &mdash; measure. Once you have a concrete number and agree
that the number going up would be a good thing, it's hard to argue
with results.  &ldquo;In God we trust, all others bring
data.&rdquo;<sup><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W._Edwards_Deming#cite_ref-learning_34-0"
target="_blank">2</a></sup> </li>
<li><em>Focus on the process:</em> Rather than evaluating how you're
performing on the basis of your current project, focus on how quickly
and how well you can push projects forward in general. If I manage to
build a cool app that makes some money, that would be nice, but if I
can eliminate a persistent source of distraction preventing me from
focusing, that may well pay off for years to come.</li>
<li><em>Manage information:</em> Data should never be unintentionally
lost, should always be secure, and should always be synchronized, so
you never get a stale version of something. You should have access to
the vast firehose of information on the net when you need it, but
should also be able to enter a flow state without distractions when
you need that. Many of these requirements are solved technical
problems, but our tools for the most part do not make use of the
solutions.</li>
</ul>

